# --- paste into ~/.claude/CLAUDE.md (always-on) instead of using the skill ---
# A skill is loaded only when the model judges it relevant; this snippet is
# always in context, so it fires more reliably for proactive "alert me" behavior.

## Voice alerts — assume I'm not watching; reach me with `vox`

Assume I am **not** looking at the terminal while you work. `vox` (a local
text-to-speech CLI; https://github.com/kohlhofer/vox) is how you get my
attention, so use it freely — **default to speaking; silence is the exception.**
I often have several jobs going, so lead with *which* one.

**Speak every time you hand the turn back to me:** I finished a task (pass or
fail, however long it took — don't wait for a job to be "long-running"); you're
blocked and need my input/decision/approval; something broke; or you're about to
go quiet on a build/deploy/long job (say so, then tell me again when it's back).

**Still stay silent for:** step-by-step narration mid-task (one note when the
turn ends, not five along the way) and quick conversational back-and-forth where
I just spoke to you and am obviously right here. One note per turn.

**What to say:** one short, conversational sentence (~6–14 words). Lead with the
concern (project/repo/process) so I can tell it apart from my other jobs; say
what happened and what you need. Headline only — never read out long messages,
errors, logs, or status; those stay on screen.

**How:** guard with `command -v vox` (silent no-op if absent); fire-and-return,
no `--wait`. Example:
`command -v vox >/dev/null && vox "The web build finished — 2 tests failed."`
